# Spec: Per-Station Metering & Pipeline Control (Revised)

**Status:** Draft / proposed
**Supersedes:** the framing and Phase-2/4 design of *Concurrent Multi-Station
Pipeline + Master Control*. The hands-off auto-dispatch chain, `requireSuperAdmin`,
and the control route/page from that spec are **carried forward**; the
concurrency-as-throughput framing and the "fairness" model are **replaced** by
what's below.
**Written for:** Claude Code (repo `aestwick/kpfk-qir`).

---

## 1. What changed, and why

The original spec was framed around throughput — raise concurrency, run stations
in parallel. That framing was wrong, and we should bury it explicitly so nobody
re-derives it:

- The pipeline is **I/O-bound on shared external resources** — Groq Whisper rate
  tier, the OpenAI org spend limit, archive bandwidth. Local concurrency cannot
  raise any of them. The concurrency bump converts "stations queuing politely"
  into "stations hitting Groq 429s in parallel." It is not the win.
- **The win is two things:** (a) the pipeline runs *hands-off* so nobody
  babysits it, and (b) the shared external budget is **deliberately allocated**
  across stations that are **not equal**.

Stations are not equal: **KPFK is production; the others are test.** So the goal
is not fairness (equal round-robin) — it's **designed priority**, expressed as a
per-station budget. And the reason this is worth real complexity is that it's a
**firewall**: the scariest failure in the system is a runaway test station
burning the shared OpenAI budget, tripping the spend limit, and killing KPFK's
production pipeline the week before a filing. Per-station metering is the
blast-radius wall that lets us trial other stations without gambling the one
filing that counts.

---

## 2. Goals / Non-goals

### Goals
- Per-station **metering** of the shared budget: ingest always-on, transcribe
  N/day, summarize N/day.
- A three-rung **control ladder** per station: auto rate-limit → soft pause →
  hard stop.
- **Trustworthy confirmation**: what the dashboard shows and what the system
  enforces are the same number.
- **Honest tenant-facing states** for users of non-KPFK stations, who never see
  Master Control.
- **Master Control** (super-admin) as a *glance-and-set* surface, not a cockpit.

### Non-goals
- QIR draft generation stays **manual** (unchanged).
- No per-station queue infrastructure (shared queues + `stationId` retained).
- No move off single VPS / Redis / Supabase.
- **No latency scheduler.** Priority is volume allocation (how much per day), not
  queue-jumping (who's next). Given the quarterly cadence, prompt ordering
  doesn't matter; eventually-correct is fine.
- Not a real-time monitoring cockpit. Daily reality is a glance.

---

## 3. Locked decisions

| Decision | Choice |
|---|---|
| Daily window | **Calendar day, midnight Pacific reset** (not rolling 24h — legible, shows a real clock time) |
| Pause behavior | **Graceful** — finish the running job, start nothing new |
| Pause + ingest | Ingest **keeps running** during pause (it's free; it's the liveness signal) |
| Hard stop | **Kills everything incl. ingest**, aborts in-flight, reversible, confirm-gated |
| Priority | Per-station **tier (production / test)** that presets the caps |
| Ingest cap | None — always on |
| Confirmation | Display and enforcement read the **same counter** |

---

## 4. Design

### 4.1 Metering model

Per station, per stage: **ingest = always; transcribe = N/day; summarize =
N/day.** Ingest is uncapped because it's the cheap stage (archive bandwidth, no
AI spend).

- **Unit:** episodes/day, as a *legible proxy* for the real scarce resource
  (Groq audio-minutes, OpenAI dollars). Counts are friendlier on a dashboard than
  minutes; just know it's a proxy — 20 three-hour shows ≠ 20 vignettes in true
  cost. Don't build minute-accounting now.
- **Mechanism:** a cap is a **gate on the existing self-requeue drain**. When a
  station's stage reaches its daily count, stop re-queuing that stage until the
  window resets at midnight Pacific. The backlog **defers, it does not drop** —
  tomorrow the chain picks up where it left off. This rides on the drain loop
  that already exists; it is a turnstile, not a new pipeline.
- **Counter = single source of truth.** One record per `(station, stage, day)`,
  keyed to midnight Pacific. The worker reads it to decide whether to keep going;
  the UI reads the *same* record to display "14 / 20 · resets 12:00 AM PT." There
  is no separate display estimate — that's what makes the meter trustworthy
  rather than decorative.
- **Tier presets.** `tier` is one field per station. `production` (KPFK) presets
  to uncapped / high; `test` presets to low. Presets are editable per station.
  This also retires the murky implicit "test = has no `rss_base_url`" — make the
  tier explicit, and it becomes a lifecycle: a station starts `test`, runs real
  audio without ever competing with KPFK's budget, and graduates to `production`
  when the flag is flipped.

### 4.2 The three-state control ladder

Exactly two things escalate down the ladder: whether ingest survives, and whether
the in-flight job survives.

| State | Trigger | Expensive stages | Ingest | Running job | Comes back |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Rate-limited** | automatic (daily cap) | stop | runs | finishes | auto, midnight PT |
| **Pause** (soft) | admin | stop | runs | finishes (graceful) | admin un-pauses |
| **Hard stop** | admin | stop | **stops** | **aborted** | admin restarts |

**Hard stop — clean abort is non-negotiable.** Aborting an in-flight transcribe
must revert the interrupted episode to `pending` with **no half-state** (no
`status='transcribed'` without a transcript row). Get this wrong and the hard-stop
button becomes a ghost-episode generator — the exact failure already paid to fix.
Honest caveat: a Groq call already sent is already billed; hard stop halts
everything *after* it, it cannot claw back the request in flight. "Kill" means
"nothing more," not "un-spend."

**Friction scales with blast radius.** Soft pause is free to hit (graceful,
reversible). Hard stop requires a **confirm**, especially on KPFK — an accidental
kill of the production station the week before filing is the precise disaster this
whole design prevents.

**Reversible, not destructive.** Restart resumes the backlog. Hard stop does
**not** wipe data or de-provision the station. Decommissioning is a separate,
slower, more-deliberate action — no single panic-click does permanent harm.

**Naming:** `Pause` / `Stop` carries the severity in the verb (Stop reads more
final). "Emergency stop" if the friction should live in the label.

### 4.3 Reliable visual confirmation

- One counter, read by both the gate and the UI (§4.1).
- **Transitional honesty:** show `pausing…` while the in-flight job is still
  wrapping up, and settle to `paused` only once it has actually stopped. Same for
  hard stop (`stopping…` → `stopped`). Never display a stopped state while a job
  is still running — that's the whole point of graceful.
- The pause/stop state the worker checks is the state the UI shows. No optimistic
  toggles.

### 4.4 Tenant-facing states (non-KPFK station users)

Other stations have their own users who **do not see Master Control** — they see
their own station's normal dashboard. A stop that doesn't explain itself reads as
broken. So every non-running state must name **its cause and its resolution**, and
answer the three questions a user is silently asking: *is it broken? why did it
stop? did I lose anything?*

| State | What the user sees |
|---|---|
| **Rate-limited** | "**Paused for the day — resumes 12:00 AM PT**" + "20 / 20 transcribed today · 6 new episodes received and queued." Calm, neutral indicator — **not** a red error. |
| **Pause** (soft) | "**Processing paused — contact your administrator**" + liveness count ("6 received and queued"), since ingest still runs. No resume clock. |
| **Hard stop** | "**Processing stopped — contact your administrator**." Fully dark — no liveness count (ingest is off), no resume time. The one state where "dark" is the honest truth. |

- The **ingestion count** is the liveness signal ("still receiving, not dead") and
  must appear *with* the cap number, not alone — alone it only proves liveness;
  together they tell the whole story (alive · why stopped · nothing lost).
- **SaaS framing:** present the rate-limit as *that station's own daily
  allowance* — neutral, per-tenant. **Never expose the KPFK-priority hierarchy.**
  "Different stations have different processing allowances" is a normal plan-tier
  truth that survives two tenants comparing notes; "KPFK eats first" is a bad look
  you'd have to walk back the day they're paying. This screen is the future
  billing-tier surface — design it neutrally once and it does both jobs.
- **Scope the stop.** Caps and pause stop only the throttled stages. Do not grey
  out the app — users can still ingest, read already-processed episodes, and work
  QIR drafts. The dashboard should read "pacing itself," not "dead."

### 4.5 Master Control (super-admin)

A glance-and-set surface, not a cockpit. The GM looks roughly once a day, and it
only truly matters one week per quarter — so the design optimizes for *legibility
on a glance after a long unattended stretch*.

- **Primary signal is time, not depth.** "This station last advanced 4 days ago"
  matters; "3 pending" is meaningless to a weekly glancer. Lead each station card
  with a **staleness clock** + loud threshold.
- **Hierarchy mirrors priority.** KPFK is the prominent card; test stations are a
  quiet row beneath. The visual order *is* the priority order.
- **Per-station controls:** edit the daily caps (transcribe/summarize N/day),
  soft pause, hard stop (confirm-gated). Global pause + steady/catch-up mode
  retained from the original spec.
- **One push channel.** Because attention is bursty (weeks off, then crunch),
  keep a single out-of-band alert: **"KPFK has gone dark"** if the production
  station hasn't advanced in ~48h. Not real-time monitoring — just the one ping
  that converts "it's probably been fine all quarter" from faith into verified.
- Reads via `requireSuperAdmin` (carried from original spec); `403` for everyone
  else; nav link hidden for non-super-admins.

### 4.6 Dispatch & concurrency (carried, with one correction)

- Hands-off auto-dispatch chain (`ingest → transcribe → summarize → compliance`
  via the `chain` flag) is carried unchanged from the original spec.
- **Per-station dedupe MUST use an atomic Redis lock** keyed on `stationId` (e.g.
  `SET NX` with a TTL refreshed per cycle, released when the chain's `remaining`
  goes false) — **not** a `getActive()`+`getWaiting()` scan. The scan is a
  check-then-act race and misses BullMQ's `delayed` set, where the zero-progress
  backoff parks jobs; under hourly auto-dispatch that stacks a second chain on a
  station and breaks the priority guarantee. The atomic lock spans every job
  state and closes the window. The DB claim guard still protects correctness; the
  lock protects the allocation.
- The concurrency bump exists only to find the external ceiling empirically
  (moderate + watch Groq 429s + one-line rollback). It is not throughput.
- **Per-station caps are now the primary allocation lever.** Global
  steady/catch-up mode still governs raw parallelism and is orthogonal; revisit
  whether catch-up still earns its keep once caps exist (Open Questions).

